Mexican Stocks: Alfa, Urbi Desarrollos, Wal-Mart de Mexico

-- B y   L e o n   L a z a r o f f
-- 
2011-04-26T20:41:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-26/mexican-stocks-alfa-embotelladoras-arca-urbi-desarrollos.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  Mexico  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4 p.m. New York time.  The IPC index rose 0.1 percent to 36,892.24.  Alfa SAB (ALFAA MM), the world’s largest producer of
aluminum engine heads for automobiles, rose 0.4 percent to
175.64 pesos as Ford Motor Co., the second-largest U.S.
automaker, said first-quarter profit rose 22 percent to the most
for the period since 1998. Ford, General Motors Co. and Chrysler
Group LLC are Alfa customers.  Urbi Desarrollos Urbanos SAB (URBI* MM) dropped 1.9 percent
to 28.34 pesos on concern that the debt level of Mexico’s third-
largest homebuilder is rising as a result of a government
subsidy that encourages apartment construction over individual
houses.  Wal-Mart de Mexico SAB (WALMEXV MM),  Latin America ’s
largest retailer, rose 1.7 percent to 35.88 pesos as central
bank Deputy Governor Manuel Ramos Francia said Mexico’s
inflation and growth look “reasonably good,” and that the
country’s economy will have a “good year.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
Leon Lazaroff in New York at 
 llazaroff@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
